### The Empty Set

Consider the set

A = { \(x:x\) is a student of Class XI presently studying in a school }

We can go to the school and count the number of students presently studying in Class XI in the school. Thus, the set A contains a finite number of elements.

We now write another set B as follows:\(\mathrm{B}=\{\ x:x\text{ is a student presently studying in both Classes X and XI }\}\)

We observe that a student cannot study simultaneously in both Classes X and XI. Thus, the set \(\mathrm{B}\) contains no element at all.

**Definition 1**: A set which does not contain any element is called the _empty set_ or the _null set_ or the _void set_.

According to this definition, \(\mathrm{B}\) is an empty set while \(\mathrm{A}\) is not an empty set. The empty set is denoted by the symbol \(\phi\) or \(\{\ \ \}\).

We give below a few examples of empty sets.

1. Let \(\mathrm{A}=\{x:1<x<2\), \(x\text{ is a natural number}\}\). Then \(\mathrm{A}\) is the empty set, because there is no natural number between 1 and 2.
2. \(\mathrm{B}=\{x:x^{2}-2=0\text{ and }x\text{ is rational number}\}\). Then \(\mathrm{B}\) is the empty set because the equation \(x^{2}-2=0\) is not satisfied by any rational value of \(x\).
3. \(\mathrm{C}=\{x:x\text{ is an even prime number greater than }2\}\). Then \(\mathrm{C}\) is the empty set, because 2 is the only even prime number.
4. \(\mathrm{D}=\{\ x:x^{2}=4,\text{ is odd }\}\). Then \(\mathrm{D}\) is the empty set, because the equation \(x^{2}\)= 4 is not satisfied by any odd value of \(x\).

### Finite and Infinite Sets

Let \(\mathrm{A}=\{1,2,3,4,5\}\), \(\mathrm{B}=\{a,b,c,d,e,g\}\), and \(\mathrm{C}=\{\ \mathrm{men\ living\ presently\ in different\ parts\ of\ the\ world\}\}\)

We observe that \(\mathrm{A}\) contains \(5\) elements and \(\mathrm{B}\) contains \(6\) elements. How many elements does \(\mathrm{C}\) contain? As it is, we do not know the number of elements in \(\mathrm{C}\), but it is some natural number which may be quite a big number. By number of elements of a set \(\mathrm{S}\), we mean the number of distinct elements of the set and we denote it by \(n\) (\(\mathrm{S}\)). If \(n\) (\(\mathrm{S}\)) is a natural number, then \(\mathrm{S}\) is _non-empty finite_ set.

Consider the set of natural numbers. We see that the number of elements of this set is not finite since there are infinite number of natural numbers. We say that the set of natural numbers is an infinite set. The sets \(\mathrm{A}\), \(\mathrm{B}\) and \(\mathrm{C}\) given above are finite sets and \(n(\mathrm{A})=5\), \(n(\mathrm{B})=6\) and \(n(\mathrm{C})=\mathrm{some\ finite\ number}\).

**Definition 2**: A set which is empty or consists of a definite number of elements is called _finite_ otherwise, the set is called _infinite_.

Consider some examples :

1. Let \(\mathrm{W}\) be the set of the days of the week. Then \(\mathrm{W}\) is finite.
2. Let \(\mathrm{S}\) be the set of solutions of the equation \(x^{2}-16=0\). Then \(\mathrm{S}\) is finite.
3. Let \(\mathrm{G}\) be the set of points on a line. Then \(\mathrm{G}\) is infinite.

When we represent a set in the roster form, we write all the elements of the set within braces \(\{\ \ \}\). It is not possible to write all the elements of an infinite set within braces \(\{\ \ \}\) because the numbers of elements of such a set is not finite. So, we represent some infinite set in the roster form by writing a few elements which clearly indicate the structure of the set followed ( or preceded ) by three dots.

For example, \(\{1,2,3\ldots\}\) is the set of natural numbers, \(\{1,3,5,7,\ldots\}\) is the set of odd natural numbers, \(\{\ldots,\neg 3,-2,-1,0,1,2\,3,\ldots\}\) is the set of integers. All these sets are infinite.

NoteAll infinite sets cannot be described in the roster form. For example, the set of real numbers cannot be described in this form, because the elements of this set do not follow any particular pattern.

