Such events A, B and C are called exhaustive events. In general, if E\({}_{1}\), E\({}_{2}\),..., E\({}_{n}\) are \(n\) events of a sample space S and if

\[\text{E}_{1}\cup\text{E}_{2}\cup\text{E}_{3}\cup\ldots\cup\text{E}_{n}=\overset {n}{\underset{i=1}{\cup}\text{E}_{i}}=\text{S}\]

then E\({}_{1}\), E\({}_{2}\),...., E\({}_{n}\) are called exhaustive events. In other words, events E\({}_{1}\), E\({}_{2}\),..., E\({}_{n}\) are said to be exhaustive if atleast one of them necessarily occurs whenever the experiment is performed.

Further, if E\({}_{i}\cap\text{E}_{j}=\phi\) for \(i\neq j\) i.e., events E\({}_{i}\) and E\({}_{j}\)are pairwise disjoint and \(\overset{n}{\underset{i=1}{\cup}\text{E}_{i}}=\text{S}\), then events E\({}_{1}\), E\({}_{2}\),..., E\({}_{n}\) are called _mutually exclusive and exhaustive events_.

