### Symmetric and Skew Symmetric Matrices

**Definition 4**: A square matrix \(A=[a_{ij}]\) is said to be _symmetric_ if \(A^{\prime}=A\), that is, \([a_{ij}]=[a_{ji}]\) for all possible values of \(i\) and \(j.\)

For example \(A=\begin{bmatrix}\sqrt{3}&2&3\\ 2&-1.5&-1\\ 3&-1&1\end{bmatrix}\) is a symmetric matrix as \(A^{\prime}=A\)

**Definition 5**: A square matrix \(A=[a_{ij}]\) is said to be _skew symmetric_ matrix if \(A^{\prime}=-A\), that is \(a_{ji}=-a_{ij}\) for all possible values of \(i\) and \(j.\) Now, if we put \(i=j,\) we have \(a_{ii}=-a_{ii}.\) Therefore \(2a_{ii}=0\) or \(a_{ii}=0\) for all \(i\)'s.

This means that all the diagonal elements of a skew symmetric matrix are zero.

For example, the matrix \(B=\begin{bmatrix}0&e&f\\ -e&0&g\\ -f&-g&0\end{bmatrix}\) is a skew symmetric matrix as \(B^{\prime}=-B\)

Now, we are going to prove some results of symmetric and skew-symmetric matrices.

**Theorem 1**: For any square matrix \(A\) with real number entries, \(A+A^{\prime}\) is a symmetric matrix and \(A-A^{\prime}\) is a skew symmetric matrix.

**Proof** Let \(B=A+A^{\prime}\), then

\[B^{\prime} = (A+A^{\prime})^{\prime}\] \[= A^{\prime}+(A^{\prime})^{\prime}\text{ (as }(A+B)^{\prime}=A^{\prime}+B^{\prime})\] \[= A^{\prime}+A\text{ (as }(A^{\prime})^{\prime}=A)\] \[= A+A^{\prime}\text{ (as }A+B^{\prime}=B+A)\] \[= B\]

Therefore \(B=A+A^{\prime}\) is a symmetric matrix

