### 10.4 Addition of Vectors

A vector \(\overline{\text{AB}}\) simply means the displacement from a point A to the point B. Now consider a situation that a girl moves from A to B and then from B to C (Fig 10.7). The net displacement made by the girl from point A to the point C, is given by the vector \(\overline{\text{AC}}\) and expressed as

\[\overline{\text{AC}}=\overline{\text{AB}}+\overline{\text{BC}}\]

This is known as the _triangle law of vector addition._

In general, if we have two vectors \(\vec{a}\) and \(\vec{b}\) (Fig 10.8 (i)), then to add them, they are positioned so that the initial point of one coincides with the terminal point of the other (Fig 10.8(ii)).

**Fig 10.8**

For example, in Fig 10.8(ii), we have shifted vector \(\vec{b}\) without changing its magnitude and direction, so that it's initial point coincides with the terminal point of \(\vec{a}\). Then, the vector \(\vec{a}\) + \(\vec{b}\), represented by the third side AC of the triangle ABC, gives us the sum (or resultant) of the vectors \(\vec{a}\) and \(\vec{b}\) i.e., in triangle ABC (Fig 10.8 (ii)), we have

\[\overline{\text{AB}}+\overline{\text{BC}}=\overline{\text{AC}}\]

Now again, since \(\overline{\text{AC}}=-\overline{\text{CA}}\), from the above equation, we have

\[\overline{\text{AB}}+\overline{\text{BC}}+\overline{\text{CA}}=\overline{ \text{AA}}=\vec{0}\]

This means that when the sides of a triangle are taken in order, it leads to zero resultant as the initial and terminal points get coincided (Fig 10.8(iii)).

Now, construct a vector \(\overline{\mathrm{BC}}^{\prime}\) so that its magnitude is same as the vector \(\overline{\mathrm{BC}}\), but the direction opposite to that of it (Fig 10.8 (iii)), i.e.,

\[\overline{\mathrm{BC}^{\prime}}=-\overline{\mathrm{BC}}\]

Then, on applying triangle law from the Fig 10.8 (iii), we have

\[\overline{\mathrm{AC}^{\prime}}=\overline{\mathrm{AB}}+\overline{\mathrm{BC}^{ \prime}}=\overline{\mathrm{AB}}+(-\overline{\mathrm{BC}})=\vec{a}-\vec{b}\]

The vector \(\overline{\mathrm{AC}^{\prime}}\) is said to represent the _difference of_\(\vec{a}\) and \(\vec{b}\).

