### Independent Events

Consider the experiment of drawing a card from a deck of 52 playing cards, in which the elementary events are assumed to be equally likely. If E and F denote the events 'the card drawn is a spade' and 'the card drawn is an ace' respectively, then

\[\text{P}\left(\text{E}\right)=\frac{13}{52}=\frac{1}{4}\text{ and P}\left(\text{F}\right)=\frac{4}{52}=\frac{1}{13}\]

Also E and F is the event'the card drawn is the ace of spades' so that

\[\text{P}\left(\text{E}\cap\text{F}\right)=\frac{1}{4}\text{ and }\text{P}\left(\text{F} \right)=\frac{52}{13}=\frac{1}{4}\]

Hence P(EIF) = \(\frac{1}{4}=\text{P}\left(\text{EIF}\right)\), we can say that the occurrence of event F has not affected the probability of occurrence of the event E.

We also have

\[\text{P}\left(\text{FIE}\right)=\frac{\text{P}\left(\text{E}\cap\text{F} \right)}{\text{P}\left(\text{E}\right)}=\frac{\frac{1}{52}}{\frac{1}{4}}= \frac{1}{13}=\text{P}\left(\text{F}\right)\]

Again, P(F) = \(\frac{1}{13}=\text{P}\left(\text{FIE}\right)\) shows that occurrence of event E has not affected the probability of occurrence of the event F.

Thus, E and F are two events such that the probability of occurrence of one of them is not affected by occurrence of the other.

Such events are called _independent events_.

